SIMPLE: setting
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Setting
<hw>Set"ting</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act
of one who, or that which, sets; <as>as, the <ex>setting</ex> of type,
or of gems; the <ex>setting</ex> of the sun; the <ex>setting</ex>
(hardening) of moist plaster of Paris; the <ex>setting</ex> (set) of a
current.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of marking the position of game, as a setter
does; also, hunting with a setter.</def> <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Something set in, or inserted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt set in it <qex>settings</qex> of stones.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xxviii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That in which something, as a gem, is set; <as>as,
the gold <ex>setting</ex> of a jeweled pin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>the time, place, and circumstances in which an event
(real or fictional) occurs; <as>as, the <ex>setting</ex> of a
novel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Setting coat</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>the
finishing or last coat of plastering on walls or ceilings.</cd> --
<col><b>Setting dog</b></col>, <cd>a setter. See <er>Setter</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 2.</cd> -- <col><b>Setting pole</b></col>, <cd>a pole,
often iron-pointed, used for pushing boats along in shallow water.</cd>
-- <col><b>Setting rule</b></col>. <fld>(Print.)</fld> <cd>A composing
rule.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Setting-up exercise</ent>⟦br⟧
